<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
YUGOSLAVIA; 
</P>
<P>
SERBS IN CROATIA DECLARE AUTONOMY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minority Serbs declared self-government in the Republic of Croatia and blocked 
roads and train lines, fueling fears that the rising confrontation could lead 
to ethnic strife, news reports and witnesses said. The Serbian National 
Council, based in the town of Knin, said it was assuming political control of 
Croatia's Serbian enclaves of about 600,000 people "to protect their human 
dignity, human and national rights." The nationalist government of Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman had no immediate response. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100290-0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 286373 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 2, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 22; Column 2; National Desk 
</P>
